Class TaskObjectsAsynchParallelExecutionRequest

  • java.lang.Object
    • parallel.distributed.RRObject
      • parallel.distributed.TaskObjectsAsynchExecutionRequest
        • parallel.distributed.TaskObjectsAsynchParallelExecutionRequest
  • All Implemented Interfaces:
    java.io.Serializable

    class TaskObjectsAsynchParallelExecutionRequest
extends TaskObjectsAsynchExecutionRequest
    auxiliary class wrapping a request for processing asynchronously TaskObjects, in networks of PDAsynchBatchTaskExecutor[Clt|Srv|Wrk] objects, breaking them up in smaller chunks if needed. Not part of the public API.

    Title: popt4jlib

    Description: A Parallel Meta-Heuristic Optimization Library in Java

    • Method Detail

      • runProtocol

        public void runProtocol(PDAsynchBatchTaskExecutorSrv srv,
                        java.io.ObjectInputStream ois,
                        java.io.ObjectOutputStream oos)
                 throws java.io.IOException,
                        java.lang.ClassNotFoundException,
                        PDAsynchBatchTaskExecutorException
        finds a free worker and submits the tasks for processing (in chunks if needed), then sends OKReply back to the (client) requestor. In case no worker is available, sends back the tasks, wrapped in a NoWorkerAvailableResponse object. Notice that in this implementation, state is kept of those tasks that have been successfully submitted, so that in case of some workers failing, when this object's runProtocol() method runs again, it will only submit those tasks that have not yet been successfully submitted. Though the submission loop is a serial for-loop, the tasks are still sent in parallel, since each submission is an "asynchronous" submission in that there is no blocking for the tasks to complete before sending the next chunk of results.
